Exploratory Data Analysis

This analysis will be structured as a stream of consciousness in that the majority of it will be graphical looks at the variables behind a red wine receiving a high quality rating. For a more complete and polished summary of the analysis, please see the bottom three graphs for substantial findings.

American wine making in the last 30 years has exploded and European wine making has existed for centuries at a very high level. Behind all the of subjective decisions a wine maker decides, this dataset shows that there is also reason to look at the chemical side of when to determine its quality. This dataset looks at nearly 1,600 wines and the 12 variables that accompany them.

Univariate Summary:

What is the structure of your dataset?
There are 1,599 wines in the dataset with 12 features (fixed acidity, volative acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol, and quality). All variables are numeric variables.

Other observations:

The mean quality rating is 6 on a scale of 1-8 (with no wine receiving below a 3)
Most wines have relatively low residual sugars with a few outliers much higher than the majority
The median of pH falls at a 3.3 and it also the most common value
Alcoholic content in wines is most commonly around 9 and 10, at the bottom of the spectrum

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?
The main features in the data set are quality, sulphates, and alcohol.
They are the most known variables and have great variability which Iâ€™m hoping will transfer into predictive power in a model.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?
There is a chance that pH could also play into whether or not a high quality score was received seeing as acidity can easily be tasted in comparison to other variables such as density.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?
I created two subsetted dataframes, one for dry wines and one for sweet wines. My hope was that they would lead to quantitatively different quality ratings but their means are very close to each other.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this? There were a few unusual distributions that I tried to normalize so that they could be more easily used in a regression model later on. I transformed sulphates with a log10 so that it went from being skewed to normal. I attempted to normalize alcohol but neither of the log10, sqrt, or reverse transformations truly made a difference.

Here we see that two of our variables do have a strong interaction. Fixed acidity and pH which makes a lot of sense seeing as pH is our scale of how acid or base a substance is. It is always good to see assumptions about variable shown by statistical tests.

The density of wine seems fairly straightforward in reseach, the weight of the liquid by volume. It seems to be affected by a few ingredients such as alcohol, sugars, etc. Here we see that itâ€™s either affecting the acidity or vice versa!

After adjusting the plot to take a closer look at concentrations of the data points, you can see that a majority of the density data is between 0.995 and 1.000. And yet even in that tightly clustered range you can see the positive correlation with fixed.acidity.

Here again you can see the clustering of the density data but this time with a much weaker correlation to residual.sugar. These variables with intercorrelation are helpful to view because they start to paint a picture of which variables might start to affect a regression model.
Itâ€™s important to remember that highly correlated variables should not both be used in a linear regression model because that can cause undesired noise and interference.

THe above graph is the first between an independent variable and the dependent variable of quality. The correlation between the two was .48 and so I expect to be using it to predict wine quality ratings. It is a little more difficult in the above graph to visualize relatedness because of the categorical nature of the dependent variable, but you are able to see that at max end of the quality spectrum there is a higher positive correlation. The boxplots are able to higlight this relationship along with the mean summary points.

To help get a better picture of quality and alcoholâ€™s relationship despite the difficulty with dealing with a categorical variable, I jittered the plot and added a linear best fit line. You can clearly see the positive relationship between the two.

Reflection

The red wine quality dataset that I explored has nearly 1,600 datapoints to examine spread out across 12 different variables. The majority of the variables were numeric with one being factorl, the variable of quality. I first made several histograms to get a feel for the distribution of the data and then performed a few transformations on it to aide in eventually fitting it to a linear regression model. The data was very complete and did not take additional cleaning.

I placed wines into 2 groups, one for sweet wines and one for dry wines. This grouping did not seem to show any strong differences between the two. I also group the wines based on their quality datapoint and looked at the differences in means of variables between them. This was helpful confirmation when deciding on most powerful explanatory variables.

I was unable to do as much intervariable analysis because so many of the variables were numeric instead of factoral. The fact that quality was factoral did help in the end as I examined a few plots with the extra layer of quality on top.

Several variables stood out very quickly in terms of being highly correlated with quality. A correlation matrix was very helpful in determining those datapoints. Alcohol, volatile acidity, and sulphates were all correlated with quality and ended up being variables in the regression model. Suprisingly so, there were a few variables that also contributed to the model that I did not expect such as chlorides. All told, though, the model was not very powerful and was able to only explain about 37% of the datapoints.

The dataset does have its downsides with one of them being only one quality rating. If the point of collecting so many different wines and their properties is to see which elements affect the rating they receive, it would be very helpful to have 5 or more ratings and then to take an average of the spread. Without this, one has to assume that the only quality rating a wine received is the absolute truth for that wine. Lastly, the region breakdown of the wines would be helpful to examine. One place I read online said that this dataset all came from Portugal. If that is the case, one could examine which wines have properties that are consistent with others in their area and if certain areas receive higher quality rankings than others.
